  "prompt": "What's the definition of vote margin?",
  "response": "Vote margin refers to the difference in the number of votes between two candidates or options in an election or referendum. It is commonly used to express the extent of victory or defeat. For example, if Candidate A receives 1,000 votes and Candidate B receives 800 votes, the vote margin is 200 votes in favor of Candidate A. The margin can be expressed as an absolute number of votes or as a percentage of the total votes cast. This measure helps to quantify how decisive the outcome of an election is.",
